;; =============================================================================
;; Spec: Progress detector stage 2 — event envelope, tool-loop + repair-loop
;;       detectors, minimal supervisor, agent-runtime wiring
;; =============================================================================
;;
;; Stage 1 (work/progress-detector-semantic-loop-detection.spec.edn,
;; landed via PR #783/#784) shipped the substrate:
;;
;;   - components/progress-detector/ — Detector protocol, anomaly schema
;;     (re-exporting components/anomaly), DetectorAnomalyData / Observation /
;;     ToolProfile / DetectorConfig schemas, tool-profile registration API,
;;     layered config merge, NullDetector + MultiDetector
;;
;; Substrate alone does not retire the threshold-bump cycle. No detector
;; actually fires; no observations are produced; no supervisor consumes
;; anomalies. The agent-runtime path still falls back to wallclock
;; stagnation-threshold + max-total guards (#779/#781/#782/#783 series).
;;
;; Stage 2 lands the smallest set that lets a real dogfood replace
;; wallclock thresholds with named, evidence-bearing anomalies:
;;
;;   - Normalized event envelope so detectors receive consistent input
;;   - Component-vendored tool profiles populating Stage 1's registry
;;   - :detector/tool-loop  (mechanical, fingerprint sliding-window)
;;   - :detector/repair-loop (port of PR #762's review-fingerprint logic
;;                            into the new component)
;;   - Minimal supervisor (:mechanical → :terminate, :heuristic → :warn)
;;   - Agent-runtime wiring so the detectors actually run on every
;;     parsed agent event for the planner, implementer, reviewer, tester
;;
;; Stage 3 still owns: phase contracts, status taxonomy, full :on-anomaly
;; policy map, composite-rules, the :prompt/liveness-watchdog rename
;; + bb migrate-prompts command, :detector/no-information-gain (which
;; needs a progress ledger), :detector/repeated-failure (parsed-failure
;; fingerprints), :detector/text-similarity, :detector/event-motif-loop.

{:spec/title "Progress detector stage 2 — event envelope + tool-loop + repair-loop + supervisor wiring"

 :spec/description
 "Land the smallest set of additions on top of the Stage 1 substrate
  that lets the agent-runtime emit named anomalies instead of wallclock
  timeouts. Concretely: a normalized event envelope on the existing
  agent event stream, the two mechanical detectors (:tool-loop,
  :repair-loop), tool-profile contributions from each tool-vendoring
  component, a minimal supervisor that consumes anomalies via the
  Stage 1 default policy (:mechanical → :terminate, :heuristic → :warn),
  and wiring at the agent.invoke boundary so detectors actually run.

  Layer cake — Stage 2 contributions in **bold**:

    Layer 1 — Budget + liveness     (cost, tokens, turns, OS-wedge)
                                    [unchanged from Stage 1]
    Layer 2 — **Event normalization**   (envelope, tool profile,
                                         fingerprints) — Stage 2
    Layer 3 — **Progress / anomaly**    (reducer detectors, anomaly facts)
                                        Stage 1 framework, Stage 2
                                        adds :tool-loop + :repair-loop
    Layer 4 — **Supervisor policy**     (anomaly composition, lifecycle)
                                        Stage 2 ships the minimal
                                        class-default policy; Stage 3
                                        owns the per-category map
    Layer 5 — Phase contracts           [Stage 3]

  ## Why this scope and not more

  The threshold-bump cycle (#779/#781/#782/#783) is a within-turn loop
  problem: agents call the same tool with the same args repeatedly,
  burning real wallclock until a wallclock threshold catches it.
  :detector/tool-loop attacks that directly. :detector/repair-loop
  attacks the same problem one level up — across-turn — and is a
  pure refactor of code that already ships (PR #762).

  The supervisor minimum is the smallest amount of policy needed to
  make detectors *do* something. Heuristic anomalies just log; only
  mechanical ones terminate. That is the Stage 1 spec's documented
  default, ported here to the actual code path.

  Everything else — :detector/no-information-gain, repeated-failure,
  text-similarity, motif-loop — depends on infrastructure (progress
  ledger, parsed-failure fingerprints, similarity indexers) we do not
  need to retire the immediate threshold-bump cycle. They land in
  Stage 3 alongside the policy surface they require.

  ## Component layout (Stage 2 additions)

    components/progress-detector/src/ai/miniforge/progress_detector/
      detectors/
        tool_loop.clj         ;; mechanical, fingerprint sliding-window
        repair_loop.clj       ;; port of PR #762's review-fingerprint
                              ;;   logic — agent.reviewer/review-fingerprint
                              ;;   + stagnated? move here intact
      supervisor.clj          ;; minimal policy: mechanical→terminate,
                              ;;   heuristic→warn; selects controlling
                              ;;   anomaly via :fatal>:error>:warn>:info,
                              ;;   ties broken :mechanical>:heuristic,
                              ;;   then earliest :event/seq
      event_envelope.clj      ;; normalize :tool/* events into the
                              ;;   Observation schema; assign
                              ;;   :event/seq per-agent-run; compute
                              ;;   :resource/version-hash for filesystem
                              ;;   reads/writes; carry :tool/error?
      runtime.clj             ;; the bind-detectors-to-an-agent-run
                              ;;   helper used by agent.invoke; owns
                              ;;   the per-run reducer state for the
                              ;;   composed MultiDetector

    components/adapter-claude-code/src/.../tool_profiles.clj
      register-profiles!      ;; called at component load; contributes
                              ;;   Read / Bash / Grep / Glob / Edit /
                              ;;   Write / WebSearch / WebFetch profiles
                              ;;   to progress-detector/tool-profile

    components/agent/src/ai/miniforge/agent/
      reviewer.clj            ;; deletes review-fingerprint /
                              ;;   stagnated? / actionable-severities
                              ;;   / issue-fingerprint / failed-gate-
                              ;;   fingerprint — they move to the
                              ;;   detector. Repair-loop call site
                              ;;   becomes (detector/observe ...)
      runtime.clj             ;; agent.invoke gains a detector pipeline:
                              ;;   open detector state at session start,
                              ;;   call observe on each parsed agent
                              ;;   event, hand anomalies to supervisor,
                              ;;   honor :terminate by cancelling the
                              ;;   in-flight LLM stream

  ## Event envelope

  Every parsed agent event becomes an Observation map (Stage 1 schema):

    {:tool/id           :tool/read | :tool/bash | :tool/grep | …
     :seq               <monotonic int, scoped per-agent-run>
     :timestamp         <inst>
     :tool/duration-ms  <int>
     :tool/input        <args map; redaction-shaped>
     :tool/output       <result; redaction-shaped>
     :tool/error?       <bool>
     :resource/version-hash {<resource-id> <hash>}}

  :resource/version-hash is computed only for tool classes that read or
  write a resource (filesystem reads/writes, git refs). For Bash, it is
  computed against the working directory's git tree-hash before and
  after the call (the Stage 1 spec calls this out as the gating field
  for mechanical-eligibility on :determinism :environment-dependent).
  For tools without a meaningful resource (WebSearch), the field is
  absent and the detector treats fingerprint repeats as :heuristic
  per the tool-profile :determinism.

  Redaction-shaped means: arg values longer than a per-key budget are
  hashed; field values matching secret-shaped regex are replaced with
  a marker. Detectors never need raw content — they hash for
  fingerprinting and hash for evidence.

  ## :detector/tool-loop

  Fingerprint dimensions come from the tool profile (Stage 1's
  ToolProfile schema, populated in Stage 2). Sliding window of recent
  fingerprints (default size 10). When the same fingerprint appears
  > N times in the window (default N=5):

    :determinism :stable-with-resource-version
      → emit anomaly with :class :mechanical :severity :error
        when :resource/version-hash is unchanged across the matches
    :determinism :stable-ish
      → emit :class :mechanical :severity :error unconditionally
        (small false-positive rate is acceptable; the agent can
         recover by varying the call)
    :determinism :environment-dependent
      → emit :class :mechanical only when :tool/error? is true on
        every match AND the parsed failure-fingerprint is identical
        (parsed-failure fingerprint is not in the envelope yet —
         Stage 2 ships a stub that hashes :tool/error message text;
         Stage 3 replaces with structured :failure/fingerprint)
      → otherwise emit :class :heuristic :severity :warn
    :determinism :unstable
      → emit :class :heuristic :severity :warn

  Defaults are configurable via the Stage 1 layered config:

    {:config/params {:tool-loop {:window-size 10
                                 :threshold-n 5}}}

  ## :detector/repair-loop (port of PR #762)

  agent.reviewer's review-fingerprint, stagnated?, actionable-severities,
  issue-fingerprint, failed-gate-fingerprint move to
  components/progress-detector/.../detectors/repair_loop.clj unchanged
  in algorithm. The agent code path becomes:

    - At review boundary: detector observes a synthetic
      :review/completed event with the review map; the detector
      computes the fingerprint and stores it in its reducer state.
    - On the next review boundary: detector observes the new event,
      compares to prior fingerprint, emits
      :anomalies.review/stagnation when matched.

  The agent.reviewer namespace keeps zero copies of fingerprint logic
  after the port. The existing PR #762 regression tests (in
  agent/test/.../reviewer_test.clj) move to the detector's test ns
  and continue to pass without behavior change.

  ## Minimal supervisor

  components/progress-detector/.../supervisor.clj exports a tiny
  surface used by the agent runtime:

    (start  [config]                       => state)
    (handle [state anomalies]              => {:state state'
                                               :decision <…>})

  Decision is one of:
    {:action :continue}                       — no anomalies or all warn
    {:action :terminate
     :anomaly <controlling anomaly map>
     :reason  <string for the event log>}

  Controlling-anomaly selection (Stage 1 spec, lifted verbatim):
    :fatal > :error > :warn > :info
    ties broken: :mechanical > :heuristic
    further ties: earliest :event/seq

  All anomalies (controlling and not) are recorded in the event log;
  only the controlling anomaly drives termination. The supervisor
  does NOT yet consult a per-category :on-anomaly map (Stage 3) —
  the policy is hard-coded at the class level here.

  ## Agent-runtime wiring

  agent.invoke gains, on the LLM-bearing path:

    1. Build the detector list per the layered config
       (:detectors/defaults [:tool-loop :repair-loop] + per-agent
       overlays read from each agent's prompt EDN)
    2. Initialize MultiDetector + supervisor state at session start
    3. Stream agent events through event-envelope normalization,
       feed Observations to MultiDetector via observe-event
    4. Hand emitted anomalies to supervisor; on :terminate,
       cancel the in-flight LLM call and record the controlling
       anomaly as the run's terminating event
    5. Persist all anomalies (controlling + non-controlling) to the
       run's local event log via :raw-log-ref

  Wiring is agent-agnostic — planner, implementer, reviewer, tester
  share the same agent.invoke path; per-agent overlays come from
  prompt EDN, not from N copies of the wiring code.

  ## What Stage 2 explicitly does NOT land

  Deferred to Stage 3:
    - :prompt/liveness-watchdog rename + bb miniforge migrate-prompts
      command (the rename is a sweeping migration; we keep
      :prompt/progress-monitor through Stage 2 and rename in one
      Stage 3 commit alongside the policy surface it gates)
    - Full :on-anomaly per-category policy map
    - Composite-rules for promoting combined heuristics → mechanical
    - Phase contracts (:phase/contract block per phase)
    - Phase status taxonomy (:succeeded / :failed-contract /
      :failed-anomaly / :failed-budget / :failed-liveness /
      :failed-tool / :cancelled / :requires-human)
    - Workflow runner enforcement of contracts at phase boundaries
    - :detector/no-information-gain (depends on progress ledger)
    - :detector/repeated-failure (depends on structured
      :failure/fingerprint extraction)
    - :detector/text-similarity, :detector/event-motif-loop
    - Replacing the Stage 2 stub failure-fingerprint with a
      structured parser per tool class"

